comment.editorialComment: This is the time of the year when the market traditionally starts to slow down and with that slow down comes the inevitability of pressure on values. The most obvious driver of this is the general lack of demand from the retail buyers but there are other factors to take into account as well. For instance, there may be a surplus of stock from recent de-fleet exercises that some of the rental operators may have done. This is also one of the biggest sectors in terms of overall volume and can be heavily affected by manufacturer short cycle business and tactical registrations. All of this puts pressure on values and we wouldn’t be surprised to see an overall drop of around -3% during the course of the month.

December is always a month where there is an expectation for the book to drop more than it has done in recent months. This year will probably be no exception to that as we will see a drop off in retail footfall and trade buyers won’t all have open cheque books at this time of the year. However, there will still be stock in the market and these vehicles will need to find homes as most of the big vendors will need to reduce their inventory before the end of the year. This means that for the buyers there are probably some bargains to be had and for those that need to stock up in anticipation of January. All of this puts pressure on values and it isn’t uncommon to see a drop of -3.5% to -4.0% during December.

This sector has seen a steady increase in volumes over the past few years but that doesn’t mean that used values should necessarily suffer as a result. January is always expected to be a strong month with many dealer groups kick starting the market by offering high profile sale events during the month. Vehicles in this sector play a big part in that as they are usually available in a variety of models across most ages and represent an attractive proposition for both trade and retail buyers alike. Dealers will be actively buying stock to help feed the demand and it is on the back of this that we would expect to see a small rise in values by the end of the month.
